{"title":"Transductive Learning for Unsupervised Text Style Transfer","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Unsupervised text style transfer methods that learn global (inductive) style rules often produce context-inconsistent expressions (e.g., choosing a style word inappropriate for the content) due to the lack of parallel supervision.","method":"Adopt a transductive paradigm (TSST) that conditions generation on specific, retrieved target-style sentences for each input. Retrieve top-K target-style sentences using either sparse BM25 or a jointly learned dense retriever, and feed them into an attention-based encoder–decoder that, at each decoding step, attends to both the input and retrieved samples. Train end-to-end with standard reconstruction, cycle, and adversarial style losses, augmented by a retrieval loss and a bag-of-words loss that encourages selecting new words from retrieved samples, yielding context-aware style expressions and improved consistency."},{"problem":"Term-based retrieval misses semantic context and style words bias similarity, making it hard to find cross-style, content-similar references needed for effective transductive transfer.","method":"Design a dense retriever built on a style-independent text embedding q(x), computed as a weighted sum of encoder hidden states with word weights α(w) initialized to down-weight style-discriminative terms based on their across-style frequency distribution. Use cosine similarity with MIPS to retrieve target-style neighbors, and jointly optimize with a retrieval loss that aligns embeddings of the input and its transferred output; embeddings are periodically refreshed during training to keep retrieval up to date."}]}
